  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions worldwide. It is considered a serious criminal offense because it involves the process of making illegally obtained money (or \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. \n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Legal Prohibition**: Money laundering is explicitly criminalized under various national and international laws. For example, in China, it is prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China** and the **Criminal Law of the People's Republic of China**.\n\n2. **International Standards**: The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an intergovernmental organization, sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Many countries, including China, are members and adhere to these standards.\n\n3. **Legal Consequences**: Engaging in money laundering can result in severe penalties, including imprisonment, fines, and confiscation of assets. In China, for instance, individuals or entities involved in money laundering can face significant criminal and administrative sanctions.\n\n4. **Purpose of Prohibition**: The prohibition of money laundering aims to combat organized crime, corruption, and terrorism financing, as well as to maintain the integrity of financial systems.\n\nTherefore, money laundering is not only ethically and socially condemned but also legally prosecuted to safeguard economic and financial stability.",
